-- WP10 (docs/spec/WASM-SEMANTICS.md §1) — the S0 SILENT arm of #553.
--
-- ⚠️ THIS FIXTURE IS CURRENTLY WRONG ON PURPOSE, AND ITS GOLDEN ASSERTS THE BUG.
-- `eager_global_call_hidden.eval.golden` says `0`. The RIGHT answer is 42 (eval says
-- 42). The golden records native's ACTUAL output because that is what this corpus's
-- goldens are by construction (capture_goldens.sh's llvm_eval block mirrors
-- diff_compiler_llvm.sh's worker exactly). The divergence is ledgered in
-- test/engine_divergence.txt as `emitter:shared-eager-init` and DRAINS when #553 lands:
-- at that moment native starts printing 42, this golden stops matching, and both this
-- gate and diff_compiler_engines go red until someone re-blesses. That is the point —
-- do NOT "fix" the golden to 42 while #553 is open, and do NOT delete this fixture.
--
-- THE BUG. A nullary top-level binding is an eagerly-initialized global. Both backends
-- order those with a topo sort whose edges come from the SHARED `eagerVars`
-- (compiler/backend/emit_support.mdk) — a DIRECT free-var scan of the binding's own
-- body that does NOT follow calls into a callee. So `cell = mkVal ()` yields the single
-- edge `mkVal`: a FUNCTION, not a value bind, hence no edge at all. `base` is invisible,
-- source order decides, and `cell` initializes first — reading `base`'s still-zero cell.
--
-- Measured on the shipping engines (2026-07-16):
--   eval   -> 42          (correct)
--   native -> 0, exit 0   (a WRONG ANSWER with no diagnostic — this is the S0)
--   wasm   -> traps "dereferencing a null pointer" at instantiate (killed the whole
--             playground; that is #543, the loud arm that got this noticed at all)
-- The severity tracks the poisoned global's TYPE: an unboxed Int reads a zero word and
-- LIES; a boxed value dereferences null and segfaults (exit 139). This fixture pins the
-- SILENT one deliberately — a fix that only silenced the crash would leave the lie live.
--
-- The peer `eager_global_call_ordered.mdk` is the CONTROL: same program, `base` moved
-- ABOVE `cell`, all three engines agree on 42. It is what proves the ONLY variable here
-- is declaration order.

mkVal _ = base

cell = mkVal ()

base = 42

main = cell
